<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Dresdner and BNP strengthen ties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dresdner Bank and Banque Nationale de Paris plan to strengthen their
partnership, established last year, by making joint acquisitions in European
countries.
The banks want to boost their position in markets where they are
under-represented.
Mr Jurgen Sarrazin, chairman of Dresdner's managing board, said yesterday
that they also intended to merge their operations in Spain in the first
quarter of next year, the first such move they have made.
He told a press conference in Madrid during the IMF/World Bank annual
meetings that the banks planned to form a joint subsidiary in Spain and buy
out minority equity holders in BNP's operation. He said the banks, which
hold small stakes in each other, intended to make joint acquisitions in
addition to opening joint operations outside their home countries. There
were no acquisition targets, but in countries such as Italy where neither
has a strong presence, they might try to acquire an existing commercial or
investment banking operation.
The BNP/Dresdner co-operation deal has been investigated by the European
Commission on competition grounds, but no decision has been taken. The banks
want to raise their cross-share holdings to 10 per cent in the long term.
The most concrete move the two banks have undertaken has been to open joint
subsidiaries in eastern Europe, including Prague, St Petersburg, and
Budapest, but Spain would be the first operational merger.
Because BNP's operation in Spain is 23 per cent owned by minority
shareholders, the restructuring would have to be accompanied by a public
offering for their shares. The two banks have established a joint working
group to plan the future of the Spanish operation. It is expected to
concentrate on large and medium-sized companies, and on private banking for
rich individuals.
FT banking conference, Page 29
</TEXT>
