<DATE>941003
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Company News (This Week): Policy of lending through
recession set to pay off - Bank of Scotland
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank of Scotland, which reports its interim results on Wednesday, is
expected to show that its policy of lending through the recession is paying
off. Market forecasts of interim pre-tax profits range from Pounds 190m to
Pounds 202m, up from Pounds 117.6m at the halfway stage a year ago. Analysts
are waiting for earnings per share figures of 9.6p-10.4p, of which about
2.1p will go in dividend.
The figures are contingent, above all, on estimates of Bank of Scotland's
bad debt provision. If it falls at the rate of other UK banks, profits would
turn out at the higher end of the range. But Scotland, which never went into
recession as deeply as other parts of the UK, has commensurately less
potential to rebound.
Other banks have achieved profit growth as the UK economy comes out of
recession. But none have improved their results at the same time as
increasing lending and income at the pace of Bank of Scotland. One analyst
forecast 9 per cent growth in total income in the year to this first half.
The next fastest growing UK bank achieved total income growth of 7 per cent
and one's figures actually declined by 4 per cent.
Bank of Scotland has had room to expand in that its business a decade ago
was exclusively north of the border. Now more is in England and Wales than
in its home territory.
Analysts have periodically speculated on the logic of an approach to an
English building society. The bank's culture remains conservative, however.
In any case, few building societies have signalled their readiness to sell
out.
Costs, as well as income, are rising at a faster rate than the sector as a
whole. But Bank of Scotland responds with irritation to suggestions that it
should now curb its expenses. The lowest cost-income ratio of major UK banks
is proof of its efficiency, Bank of Scotland believes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Bank of Scotland.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6021 National Commercial Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
