<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Woolworth chief out after rift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr William Lavin, the chief executive of Woolworth, has unexpectedly left
the US retailer less than five months after being stripped of the
chairmanship over the disclosure that the company had falsified financial
reports. Mr Lavin's departure, and the announcement that Woolworth is
starting a search for a new chief executive from outside, throws further
doubt on the future of the troubled group. Hit by growing losses, the
company was forced to cut its quarterly dividend from 29 cents to 15 cents
in July.
Woolworth said Mr Lavin's departure was due to differences with the board
over the future direction of the company. It refused to say what the
differences were, and Mr Lavin could not be contacted for comment. Mr Lavin
has resigned as chief executive, vice chairman and a director, 'effective
immediately', Woolworth said.
The disagreement over strategy throws into doubt the restructuring pursued
by Mr Lavin and raises the spectre of further asset sales. Mr Lavin has
slashed Woolworth's US general merchandise stores and sold its chain of
discount stores in Canada, while expanding in speciality retailing. But
continuing pressure on profit margins in the US and disappointing results in
Europe led to a jump in losses in the second quarter.
Mr Lavin had been reinstated as chief executive in May, after stepping aside
pending the outcome of an internal investigation into of accounting
policies. That review found quarterly financial reports in 1993 had been
deliberately misstated to allow it report profits rather than losses.
</TEXT>
