<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The nation's appetite for crime series, factual or fictional, is
inexhaustible. That at least is the view of the television companies. The
Nick (Channel 4 at 9pm) is real life, a fly-on-the-wall documentary which
follows the force of Gipton station in Leeds as it patrols a large chunk of
the inner city. Camera teams follow both CID and the uniform branch as they
respond to emergencies. The idea has taken a firm grip in the US, where
virtually every police car has a cameraman in the back, and sadly it should
prove riveting viewing here.
Equally investigative is Panorama (BBC 1 9.30) where, to mark the opening of
the Labour Party Conference, Tony Blair is brought face to face with five
representatives of middle England who try and uncover what he stands for.
Alan Rickman (star of Truly, Madly, Deeply) is not a great one for self
promotion, but he is producing and raising the money for his latest venture,
Mesmer, about the 18th century pioneer of hypnotism. The late Dennis Potter
wrote the script and filming is under way in Hungary where BBC 2's cameras
catch up with him at 11.15.
</TEXT>
