<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain chugged on to the information superhighway last Friday with what is
claimed to be its first public trial of digital interactive television.
The trial is taking place in Cambridge and involves only 10 households at
present, but the intention is to extend it to more than 1,000 customers by
the end of next year. Customers are able to select from a menu of services
including movies, local news and weather. No charge is being made for the
trial, but the service should be fully commercial from mid-1996.
The trial is being run by a consortium including Anglia Television, ATM and
Cambridge Cable, and is led by Online Media, a member of the Acorn Computer
Group owned by Olivetti of Italy. Cambridge Cable has some 67,000 homes in
the Cambridge area on its fibre optic network.
Multimedia specialists are agreed that the Cambridge trial, although
small-scale, could prove a milestone for the multimedia industry.
Christopher Cowan, multimedia specialist with Andersen Consulting, said that
an important feature was the use of a technology called Asynchronous
Transfer Mode (ATM) to deliver multimedia services to the home.
ATM offers huge transmission capacity and is seen by many as the technology
that will underpin multimedia developments in the future.
Malcolm Bird, Online Media's chief executive, said the purpose of the trial
was to test ATM technology in the real world. A small selection of movies,
news reports, documentaries and educational programmes were available for
transmission.
A key component of the trial is the 'set-top box' responsible for decoding
the stream of digital information from the network and transforming it into
sound and pictures. The Online Media box uses a microprocessor built by
Advanced Risc Machines, in which Acorn has a significant stake.
Bird says there had been interest from potential content-providers including
Independent Television News, Woolworth and Philips Media. Woolworth was
providing an electronic shopping catalogue, although it was not yet possible
to use the system to order goods.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
