<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: New lyrics written for an old
song - The shadow chancellor tells Philip Stephens about strategies to boost
investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gordon Brown calls it the 'New Economics'. It is not new. But for his
party the approach certainly is different.
Last week saw the shadow chancellor join Mr Tony Blair in ditching the
party's traditional assumption that higher spending and taxes would solve
the economy's problems.
Neither man will produce detailed tax tables this far ahead of a general
election. But apart from the 'undeserving rich' (no-one is quite sure who
they are, although the bosses of the newly privatised utilities seem one
obvious choice), Mr Brown's message is that the nation's taxpayers can sleep
soundly.
Convinced that the break with the past has now been made, Mr Brown wants to
move on to a more positive agenda - explaining what Labour would do rather
than what it would not.
The thread running through his efforts to present a credible strategy at the
next general election is the diagnosis that under-investment is the key to
the UK's economic weakness.
In an interview with the Financial Times on the eve of today's conference
debate on the economy, Mr Brown offered Labour's answer: a framework for the
economy in which the productive base would be rebuilt by a government
working with rather than against the private sector.
The idea that Britain has for too long lived for the short term is hardly
novel. Politicians and economists have spent much of the past 30 years
telling us of the dangers of preferring today's consumption to tomorrow's
investment.
Nor is there anything new about the idea that the nation's education system
is no match for that of the Japanese or the Germans; or that British
companies often prefer hefty dividend payments to long-term expansion
programmes.
What has changed is Labour's prescription. State direction and ownership,
like high spending and punitive taxes, Mr Brown insists, are no longer part
of Labour's agenda.
The message he wants the voters - and business - to take came in the first
sentence of the interview: 'I think the key thing is for people to
understand that Labour is setting aside the old conflicts between the public
and private sectors. We see a partnership that is essential to the
regeneration for the economy.'
The Tories have failed because they have presided over an ever-shrinking
productive base. For the same reason Labour could not solve the problems by
pumping up demand. It would hit the same capacity constraints. The supply
side rules in Mr Brown's 'New Economics'.
The shadow chancellor is not offering a blueprint for the promised
transformation. The details of proposals to expand training, change the
culture of short-termism in the City and raise the level of industrial
investment must await the deliberations of party's Economic Commission.
But he sketched out the main elements of what amount to a series of carrots
and sticks to influence industry: 'We are looking at the merits of an
employer rebate/levy scheme to encourage training. We are looking at how we
can re-gear industrial and regional incentives so that they have a far
bigger component for investment in skills. We are looking at the idea of
individual training accounts and at major reform of National Insurance in
terms of the benefits people could expect for the same contributions.'
There is more: a university for industry and the possibility of tax
incentives to encourage pension funds and companies to enter into voluntary
long-term investment arrangements which would ease the pressure for large
dividends.
Labour would tighten competition policy by introducing public-interest
criteria for mergers and takeovers. It might form a development bank to help
small companies.
Alongside these proposals, Mr Brown is suggesting that the scope for
partnerships between the public and private sectors to improve the nation's
economic fabric could stretch well beyond traditional areas such as
transport. Inner-city regeneration, training and defence industry
diversification all look promising areas.
It is easy to spot the sticks and carrots. Employers would have to pay the
training levy. Rebates would depend on their performance in improving
skills. The system would 'encourage people to do what they would otherwise
consider doing themselves. It stops the good firms being undermined by the
bad so there is a case for intervention.'
Alongside this is the carrot provided by a plan to use the National
Insurance system to provide individuals with training credits - credits
which could be drawn while in work as well as between jobs.
New competition rules fall into the stick category. A public-interest
judgment on mergers and takeovers is 'very much part of our industrial
strategy'. The problem is that 'Britain has too few successful companies'.
But Mr Brown recognises the constraints on this particular assault. European
Union rules limit freedom for action and: 'Of course we recognise also that
there are many takeovers or mergers that are actually in the public
interest.'
There is also pressure on companies that are potential takeover targets to
pay high dividends rather than re-invest more of their surpluses: 'I think
it is true to say that Pounds 14 is invested for every Pounds 1 paid in
dividends in Japan but only Pounds 3 sterling is invested for every Pounds 1
paid in dividends in Britain.'
It is here that Mr Brown hints that Labour would keep stamp duty on share
transactions. But another proposal - the encouragement of long-term
investment agreements - would be on an entirely voluntary basis. If tax
incentives pushed shareholders and company boards into taking a long-term
view of their mutual interest, it would be money well spent.
Sir David Walker suggested something along the same lines when he headed the
Securities and Investments Board. The partnership theme returns, but this
time it is between finance and industry.
Overall it is not a strategy likely to bring the rank and file members to
their feet during today's debate. To do that Mr Brown will return to more
traditional themes such as boardroom greed. But Labour's 'new economics' is
a departure. The party has come terms with capitalism and is considering how
to make it work rather than dismantling it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<XX>
People:-
</XX>
<PE>Brown, G shadow chancellor.
</PE>
