<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Portillo disdains minimum
wage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservatives last night launched a renewed onslaught on Labour's plans
for a national minimum wage as unions signalled their determination to
ensure that the party fixes a specific rate before the next election.
Mr Michael Portillo, the employment secretary, anticipated today's Labour
conference debate on the issue by releasing a long dossier of independent
analyses which he said reinforced the Tories' case that a minimum wage would
destroy jobs.
Advocacy of a minimum wage demonstrated that Labour's modernisation claims
were fraudulent, he continued. Such a measure would 'drive up inflation and
could cost up to 2m jobs, harming the very people we should be trying to
help'.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, will reaffirm during the debate the
party's commitment to the principle of a minimum wage. But at the insistence
of Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, the motions supported by the leadership
make no mention of a specific figure.
Mr Blair has made clear that he wants to wait until much closer to the
election before making any specific commitment and has refused to endorse
the formula favoured by the unions of a rate fixed to half median male
earnings.
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU general union with 825,000
affiliated votes at the conference, said his union wanted to reaffirm the
existing position as laid out in policy documents published before the 1992
general election. 'On today's figures this would amount to a statutory
minimum wage of Pounds 4.05 an hour,' he said.
Mr John Edmonds, the GMB general union's general secretary, said the party's
existing minimum-wage policy would stand 'until it is changed'.
He added that the party's Economic Commission would decide on a new target
figure for the minimum wage by the next party conference, but it would be
based on the formula of half median male earnings.
Mr Edmonds also said that Labour must also agree to a precise target for the
achievement of full employment by the time of the next general election. He
added: 'We have to say where the new jobs will come from, how many there
will be and how quickly they will come.'
Support for a more flexible approach to the issue came yesterday from Mr
Gavin Laird, general secretary of the AEEU engineering union, who said:
'There needs to be further discussion before the drawing up of Labour's
election manifesto.'
</TEXT>
