<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Sale of Grid may face big tax setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Regional electricity companies could face a tax bill of more than Pounds 1bn
from their planned flotation of National Grid after a potential setback in
talks with the Inland Revenue.
The tax authority has told them it is unable to comment on a scheme by which
they hope to keep capital gains tax liability to a minimum in demerging the
Grid, which transmits electricity in England and Wales, from their
companies.
Although the regional electricity companies are seeking guidance, executives
fear the Revenue's noncommittal approach means they may have to proceed with
the issue unresolved. At worst it could signal the end of their plans to
minimise capital gains tax.
Pressure is growing on the government to get as much benefit as possible for
taxpayers and consumers from the Grid flotation. It has been criticised for
undervaluing the regional companies when it privatised them four years ago.
The Grid flotation is bound to increase the criticism because the company
was valued at just over Pounds 1bn in 1990, but is now estimated to be worth
at least Pounds 4bn.
Theoretically the government could use its golden share in each regional
company to extract windfall payments after the Grid flotation. Its
free-market principles mean it is highly unlikely to do so. It would prefer
them to cut power bills voluntarily as a means of minimising the political
flak of the Grid flotation. Capital gains tax would provide another way of
doing do.
The Revenue's remarks, in a letter to the companies follow several months of
talks.
Their proposal, through which the Grid would be demerged with an issue of
shares in the transmission company to existing shareholders, is the second
to be presented to the Revenue. The first was rejected outright.
The 'no comment' on the second scheme does not rule out talks, but some
executives fear it may mean that the Revenue will not give any proposal
prior approval. 'We may have to go ahead with a demerger without knowing
whether we will have to pay capital gains tax', said one.
Another interpretation of the letter is that it is a stalling tactic while
the government sorts out the other sensitivities surrounding the flotation.
The regional companies argue that there should be no tax liability because
the shareholders already own the Grid. 'Shareholders will have to pay
capital gains tax when they sell the Grid shares. Levying CGT on the recs at
Grid flotation would mean the tax was being paid twice,' said one executive.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
