<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / KPMG may publish its own results in full
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's second-biggest accountancy partnership said yesterday it would
publish full financial results if its clients backed a plan to incorporate
its audit practice.
KPMG Peat Marwick confirmed that it is to consult clients, investors, and
regulators with a view to creating a limited company to audit its clients
which are public limited companies.
Other options, including the incorporation of the whole business, were
dismissed at a board meeting last week. The firm audits one-fifth of all the
UK's listed companies.
If incorporation goes ahead it would be the first such venture in a leading
accounting firm. Publication of results would also be a first, except for a
brief attempt in 1979 by Arthur Andersen, which was not repeated.
Mr Colin Sharman, KPMG's senior partner, said: 'We intend to reach a final
decision early in 1995.' He added that if incorporation of audit went ahead
KPMG would move to publication of full financial results for its whole
business. Such moves could prompt the most radical restructuring of the
profession since the begining of the last century.
Several other leading accountancy firms are known to be discussing
incorporation. Publication of financial details is likely to bring into the
public arena information on what partners earn, fee structures, and details
on profits.
KPMG has 600 partners and 9,000 staff, and reported a profit of Pounds 498m
last year. The new audit company would have 200 partners and would take a
large share of the Pounds 200m now earned in the audit and accounting
division.
The new audit company would be owned by the partners, including those left
in the original partnership, and would itself be independently audited.
There are no plans for a flotation.
Initial reaction among large corporate clients to the scheme is said to be
positive but KPMG is cautious about the consultation process. 'This is a big
step; we don't want to shoot ourselves in the foot,' Mr Sharman said.
'It is vital that we gain the views of our clients on being serviced by a
limited company, that the regulatory authorities and the investment
community have no fundamental objections, that government bodies will accept
a changed status and, of course, that incorporation is acceptable to our
partnership.'
The driving force behind incorporation is the desire to limit the liability
of partners. Recent corporate collapses have resulted in litigation against
auditors who are seen as having 'the deepest pockets'.
While a new KPMG audit company could still be sued as a corporate entity,
most of the partners would have their own wealth protected. However,
individual partners could still be sued personally. Incorporation also means
that new partners would be protected from becoming liable for outstanding
legal actions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
