<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Welsh Development Agency 'is fighting for its life'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, WALES and WEST CORRESPONDENT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Welsh Development Agency is fighting for its life, says a report
published today by the Department of City and Regional Planning at the
University of Wales, College of Cardiff.
The report by Professor Kevin Morgan says the Welsh Office is 'seemingly
unsure as to whether it (the agency) ought to have a future at all'.
He states that the Welsh Office, chastened by accusations of failing to
regulate quangos properly, had thrown the agency into disarray by recently
rejecting its corporate plan. The publicly funded agency, the leading quango
in Wales, had been informed 'it should go back to the drawing board to
justify its very existence'.
The report is the first substantial analysis of the agency's role since it
became embroiled in controversy after criticism by the Commons public
accounts committee last year.
The senior management has since been replaced and the agency restructured.
Prof Morgan argues that the new managers, recruited from the private sector,
have been 'novices in the art of political bargaining'. They failed in
consequence to appreciate the significance of the annual corporate plan in
the public expenditure round at a time when the Welsh Office was under
renewed Treasury pressure to look for savings.
'Having remedied its internal governance problems, it (the agency) now finds
itself fighting for its life,' he states. 'While it is perfectly proper for
quangos to justify their existence, to precipitate a crisis in the WDA at
this delicate point in its career raises the question as to whether the
Welsh Office is genuinely interested in having a robust development agency
in Wales.'
Prof Morgan suggests the crisis at the agency stems partly from the fact
that Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, comes from a radically different
Conservative tradition to that of Mr Peter Walker and Mr David Hunt, his
predecessors. Mr Redwood had had an 'unnerving effect on the key Welsh
institutions, including the Welsh Office, by extolling the market and by
being less than effusive about the role of public-sector bodies like the
WDA'.
The report defends the agency for its positive role in modernising the Welsh
economy and enhancing the environment. It 'deserves to have a future.
Indeed, it seems surprising that there should be a question about this when
the English regions are desperately trying to create their own versions of
the WDA.'
Arguing that such institutions need to be effective and accountable, Prof
Morgan says the agency needs to develop better networking skills. He
comments that although the Welsh Office is ideally placed to promote a
networking ethos, and is formally committed to partnerships, it 'seems more
concerned to retain control for itself than to empower the wider network'.
The Fallible Servant. Department of City and Regional Planning, UWCC, PO Box
906, Cardiff CF1 3YN. Pounds 12.
</TEXT>
