<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Councils spar with Audit Commission on reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
District councils are in conflict with the Audit Commission over how much
money can be spent in preparation for the local government review.
Labour-controlled Southampton asked if it could appoint managers to plan the
takeover of responsibilities after the Local Government Commission
recommended it for unitary status, which would require it to take control of
education and social services. But the Audit Commission's legal advice was
that the council could only undertake a limited range of activities until
the orders to create a new unitary council had received royal assent.
It said: 'In a case like Southampton or Bristol, the present county council
is responsible for education and social services. It is the county council
which must collect the information about these services that will be
necessary to ensure a smooth transfer of functions.'
The cross-party Association of District Councils pointed out that not all
the councils involved were willing to plan for new unitary councils while
there was still a chance that change could be avoided.
Mr John Truscott, the leader of Southampton city council, said: 'There
doesn't appear to be any logic to it.' He added councils would have to work
to a tight timetable next year, with orders passed by MPs in February at the
earliest, and 'shadow elections' for councillors to supervise creation of
the new councils in May.
Southampton is a member of the English Major Cities group of district
councils which is calling for the government to treat them as a 'special
case'. The group also includes Bristol, Derby, Hull, Leicester, Nottingham,
Plymouth, Portsmouth and Stoke-on-Trent.
</TEXT>
