<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / OFT rejects City pleas over report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading has decided to publish a controversial report on
fixed underwriting commissions which leading City investment banks and
institutional investors have been lobbying to have shelved.
The report, commissioned by the OFT and prepared by Professor Paul Marsh of
the London Business School, concludes that securities firms and fund
managers earn excessive profits on their standing fee for underwriting
equity offerings.
The report concludes that the fixed fee of 2 per cent distributed between
the corporate adviser, broker and institutional investor is too high for the
risks undertaken.
The securities firms and fund managers fear that publication of the report
will reflect badly on the reputation of the City and will be misinterpreted
by those outside the industry.
It is understood that the OFT's inquiry into fixed underwriting commissions
has the backing of the Treasury which has been concerned that the overall
cost of raising capital in London is too high and will erode London's
competitiveness over time.
It is expected that the report will be published later this month or early
next month as one of a series of 'research reports' which the OFT has
prepared. It is believed that it will include a summary from Sir Bryan
Carsberg, director-general of fair trading. However, the report will also
include a summary of the objections which the securities industry has been
raising about its methodology.
The securities industry has argued that in rights offerings, the fixed
commission of 2 per cent reflects the need to guarantee the placement of a
large volume of securities with institutions during a six-week period.
Instead, the varying risks of individual issues are reflected in the
discount to the prevailing market price at which the new securities are
sold. Negotiating fees on each new deal would be a practical impossibility,
it says.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
