<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Thailand to get British university
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Work has begun in Thailand on the first British university to be built
outside the UK. It will be staffed by British academics and award degrees
validated by parent universities in the UK.
Ministers hope that the project, led by the Department of Trade and
Industry's education and training group, will be the first of several
British universities throughout the Pacific Rim and the Middle East,
following the model of international American universities.
Baroness Perry, leader of the group which was set up a year ago to boost UK
educational exports, said the project was needed to co-ordinate exports by
British universities and to reverse inroads made in the market by
higher-education institutions from Germany, the US and Australia.
Funding for the university is coming exclusively from Thai financiers. It
will be a private institution, with local people paying for tuition.
Lady Perry said: 'A British degree has international currency, and Thai
people will be more than willing to pay for it.'
The university aims to accept its first students in October 1996 and will
eventually cater for about 10,000 students. Two campus sites have been
designated, one of which will specialise in finance and economics, while the
other will concentrate on engineering and technology.
The project hopes to win final approval from the Thai government in July,
once detailed arrangements on appointments of administrators and lecturers
have been finalised.
Mr Richard Needham, trade minister, said there was scope for similar
initiatives elsewhere in the Pacific Rim, as several nations, including
Korea and Taiwan, have a shortage of university places compared with the
numbers that graduate from secondary school.
Several British universities are already active in the area although the
Thai project is the most ambitious. For example Warwick University, which is
not taking part in the new project, has separate manufacturing departments
in Hong Kong and Kuala Lumpur and plans to offer accounting and finance
courses from Shanghai.
The DTI group also aims to expand British higher education in Latin America,
where it has so far made few inroads.
</TEXT>
