<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Double blow for postal sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government plans to privatise the Post Office have received a double blow
from Ulster Unionist MPs and Conservative constituency associations.
With the cabinet set to decide soon whether to proceed with the sale of 51
per cent of Royal Mail, the nine Ulster Unionist MPs at Westminster have
sent a formal submission to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, saying they oppose the move.
Meanwhile, a poll of the people who chair Conservative constituency
associations has indicated that even these party ultra-loyalists favour
keeping the Post Office in the public sector - but with greater commercial
freedom.
The government's proposals have met with a succession of critical responses
in recent weeks, culminating on Friday when they were roundly condemned by
the industry's leading user group.
Leading supporters of privatisation within the cabinet such as Mr Heseltine
and Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, have recently appeared confident that
formal approval for the sell-off would be granted. But Mr John Major has not
yet made up his mind. The prime minister is wary about the potential
political cost of a decision which Labour says will signal a significant
rundown in rural post services and the closure of many village Post Offices.
Unionist opposition would significantly increase the risk of embarrassing
Commons defeats for the government.
Dissident Tory backbenchers have been calling for a minority sale of Royal
Mail, with the government retaining 51 per cent of the shares.
Mr John Taylor, Ulster Unionist MP for Strangford, said that Unionists did
not 'like the idea of the Royal Mail ceasing to operate' in Ulster. 'I have
had more letters on this subject in the last four weeks than on any subject
for the last 10 years,' he said.
The MORI survey of more than 100 of the people who chair Tory constituency
associations was commissioned by Post Office unions. It found that 57 per
cent of those questioned favoured keeping all the Post Office in the public
sector.
Mr Heseltine's favoured option is to privatise Royal Mail and Parcelforce
while hiving off the Post Office's Counters division, which is responsible
for high-street and village Post Offices, into a separate organisation in
the public sector.
</TEXT>
