<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Hospital offers land in return for services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A leading London hospital plans to give away land and buildings on its
prestigious Chelsea site to private bidders willing to develop and run
hospital services.
The proposal, by the Royal Brompton National Heart &amp; Lung Hospital Trust, is
one of the most novel responses to government calls for more private finance
in the National Health Service.
Private consortia have been invited to finance and build a Pounds 20m second
phase of the hospital's redevelopment programme, housing outpatients'
clinics and research departments. An unusual feature of the proposal is a
requirement that the development consortium will also have to run a range of
the hospital's support services - including catering, domestic and off-site
laboratories - for seven years, and manage its 28-bed private-patient unit.
The idea generated bids from 14 private-sector consortia. These have been
reduced to four, and the hospital's board is due to select a partner with
which it will enter detailed negotiations on October 11.
Formal government approval will then be required but ministers are already
aware of the plan. Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, said in June
that involving the private sector offered the NHS real advantages and could
improve services for patients. Some potential private-sector partners,
however, accuse senior NHS managers and officials of showing unnecessary
caution towards joint ventures, and the Royal Brompton proposal is regarded
as an important test of the health department's willingness to endorse
imaginative schemes.
The successful bidder's payment will be the opportunity to redevelop a
redundant clinical building and nurses home - located in one of the
capital's most sought-after residential areas - and part of the hospital's
phase-two site bordering King's Road, Chelsea. Construction groups
submitting bids include George Wimpey, Tarmac and Sir Robert McAlpine. The
plan to transfer the support services - which cost around Pounds 5m a year -
to the private sector as part of the deal has brought construction groups
and property developers into partnership with contract-service
organisations.
Mr Bill Bain, Royal Brompton chief executive, said: 'We aim to achieve the
expansion of the hospital at no cost to the taxpayer, hopefully doing so in
a way which will improve overall efficiency and enable us to lower our
prices in the NHS internal market.'
The hospital has engaged Newchurch, venture management consultants, and
Hambros Bank to help develop its plans. Mr Bain acknowledged that critics
might fear the Royal Brompton risked disposing of valuable sites too
cheaply. But he added: 'We are not commercially naive. The hospital
management is taking top quality advice.'
</TEXT>
