<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / World Trade News: Japanese take pacts in their stride
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's business community had resigned itself to some market opening
agreement before the partial accord covering US-Japanese trade issues was
announced, Michiyo Nakamoto writes from Tokyo. Even the car industry, which
could be adversely affected by the US decision to initiate a Section 301
investigation of the replacement parts industry, took the latest US verdict
in its stride.
'Once the business environment improves it will be possible to prove that
the Japanese market is not closed,' one industry official commented.
In the glass industry there was relief that the talks did not result in
sanctions, as well as a sense that their claims about the openness of the
market had been vindicated. 'The flat glass market in Japan is by no means
closed and we will aim to meet our users' satisfaction in line with the
anti-monopoly law,' Mr Kazuo Shinya, vice-president of Asahi Glass, said.
The main concern for Japanese business has not been so much the impact of
likely sanctions, which has never been considered significant, as the
adverse effect another rupture with the US could have on currency rates.
</TEXT>
