<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / World Trade News: More Japanese car exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan and the European Commission have revised upwards their forecasts for
exports of Japanese cars to the EU by 9,000 cars, a rise of 1.3 per cent
against the 1993 agreement.
The increase formed part of an agreement in July 1991 allowing for a
transitional period during which time Japan will monitor exports to the EU
and the five member states that previously restricted imports. It reflects
the unexpectedly higher number of vehicle registrations this year. The
Commission and the Japanese government now predict that demand this year
will increase this year by 4.4 per cent. The forecast of exports to the five
member states that previously restricted imports are France, 78,500; Italy,
47,000; Portugal 39,500; Spain, 35,500; UK 184,600.
</TEXT>
