<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 94 / Calls for Crimea to lose its autonomy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW KAMINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Crimea's ongoing political struggle is prompting increasingly loud calls in
Kiev for the Ukrainian peninsula's status as an autonomous republic to be
revoked.
This follows the Crimean parliament's decision on Thursday to strip
President Yuri Meshkov of most powers, as it did a month before. Mr Meshkov
at that time suspended parliament but later relented without the row being
resolved.
If the crisis continues, Kiev must take direct control of Crimea, said Mr
Vladimir Mukhin, the Ukrainian parliament's defence committee chairman.
While Moscow considers the present dispute an internal Ukrainian matter, any
move to weaken the republic's autonomous status might bring Russian
involvement.
Transferred to Ukraine in 1954, the peninsula is the sorest point in
relations between Russia and Ukraine since the Soviet Union's collapse in
1991. Under pressure from Russian nationalists, a clause on Ukrainian
territorial integrity leaving Crimea outside Russia is the main issue
holding up agreement on a Ukrainian-Russian co-operation treaty under
discussion.
Crimean deputies today are expected to consider amending the constitution to
validate last week's step, which Mr Meshkov called a 'coup d'etat'.
