<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 94 / Indian trade hit by plague panic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India's businessmen were yesterday counting the growing economic cost of the
plague, with tourism and food exports the two sectors hardest hit.
The disease, which has killed about 50 people with another 2,500 cases
suspected, has disrupted the travel trade and exports. Hotels and tour
operators, gearing up for the tourist season, have reported cancellations by
groups from Europe, the Far East and North America. Some business visitors
have cancelled trips. At least three trade fairs have been postponed.
Trade with the Gulf states, worth Dollars 3bn (Pounds 1.8bn) a year, has
been badly affected by Gulf governments' decisions to close air and sea
links with India. The biggest impact is on exporters of fresh food, who rely
on the Gulf for 70 per cent of overseas sales, worth Dollars 177m last year.
'After three years of effort in promoting exports we are back at square
one,' said Mr Gian Nega, assistant director of the Agricultural and
Processed Food Products Export Development Authority.
Health officials, including Dr NK Shah, the resident representative of the
World Health Organisation, accused the Gulf countries and other states that
have cut trade links of over-reacting.
The Indian government has launched a campaign aimed at calming the fears of
tourists, business travellers and importers of Indian goods. Mr T. Khanna,
commerce secretary, expressed concern at the potential damage to Indian
trade. 'There has been a panic reaction from some of our trading partners.
But I believe it will soon blow over.'
In London, Mr Manmohan Singh, the finance minister, said the countries that
had imposed restrictions on travel and imports risked hampering efforts to
deal with the problem. 'We are trying to create an atmosphere where people
have confidence that plague is no longer an incurable disease,' he said.
An official of KLM, the Dutch airline, in Delhi estimated that 25-30 per
cent of tourists who had planned to travel to India by KLM this week and
next had cancelled. Other European airlines, including British Airways,
Lufthansa and Swissair, also reported cancellations by tourist groups.
The disease claimed two lives in the capital, Delhi, yesterday - the first
reported deaths outside the western city of Surat where plague broke out
last week.
In the the UK, the health department said yesterday its plague surveillance
system had identified eight people showing flu-like symptoms 'who may be
infected'. But the Communicable Diseases Surveillance Centre said later that
medical tests had cleared seven, while the eighth was unlikely to have the
plague.
Growth forecast, Page 3
</TEXT>
